Abiodun Nejo, Ado Ekiti The Ekiti State Governor, Dr Kayode Fayemi, has allayed fears over the possibility of food shortage in the state post-COVID-19. He assured the people of his administration’s continued support for farmers, as well as plans to attract investments in the agricultural sector to ensure food sufficiency. The Commissioner for Information, Muyiwa Olumilua, said this in a statement in Ado Ekiti on Thursday. Olumilua explained that various steps were in the pipeline to ensure the state did not experience post-COVID-19 food shortage in addition to what had been done to boost agriculture. He said, “Governor Fayemi promised to do more to support farmers with inputs and necessary access to agricultural loan, as well as attract further big private sector players into the agricultural sector of the state.” The commissioner equally said the council approved the memorandum on the Ekiti State Mortgages and Foreclosure Bill 2020 to ensure that low income earners could access mortgages to build their own homes. Copyright PUNCH.
